{
  "doc_id": "36327",
  "text": "T RACKING objects of interest is an important and challenge problem in intelligent visual surveillance systems [CITATION_1] . visual object tracking [CITATION_2] is a long-standing problem in computer vision, there are a great amount of efforts made in visual object tracking within single cameras [CITATION_3] , [CITATION_4] . Since the visual surveillance systems provide huge amount of video streams, it is desirable to develop algorithms to track those objects of interest instead of human. In intelligent visual surveillance systems [CITATION_5] , [CITATION_6] , due to the finite camera field of view, it is difficult to observe the complete trajectory of objects of interest in wide areas with only one camera. Hence, it is desired to enable the intelligent visual surveillance system to track the objects of interest within multiple cameras [CITATION_7] . In additional, for practical considerations in installing a intelligent visual surveillance system, it is usually to have the cameras with no overlapping areas. Thus, the intelligent visual surveillance system should be able to track objects of interest across multiple non-overlapping cameras. In this paper, we focus on addressing the problem of tracking objects of interest across multiple non-overlapping cameras.",
